<P><H1 align=center>MORTGAGE REPAYMENT TYPES</H1>
<P></P>
<A NAME="InterestOnlyMortgage"></A><P><H3>Interest only mortgage: </H3>
<P></B>the borrower pays only interest on the capital to the lender, meaning 
that all the capital borrowed is still outstanding at the end of the mortgage 
term. </P>
<P>The capital is normally repaid by purchasing a long-term investment product 
at the same time the mortgage is taken out, for example an endowment policy.</P>
<P>The borrower makes payments to the endowment policy provider and at the end 
of the term, the amount received should be sufficient to repay the mortgage 
capital.</P>
<P></P>

<A NAME="CapitalAndInterestMortgage"></A><P><H3>Capital and interest mortgage : </H3>
<P>Also known as ‘Repayment Mortgage’.</P>
<P>Repayments made to the lender consist of capital and interest, meaning that 
by the end of the term, all the capital has been repaid. </P>
<P>At the start of the mortgage term, the repayments will consist mostly of 
interest, however as the capital balance reduces, so does the interest, and in 
the latter stages of the term, repayments consist mostly of capital.</P>
<P></P>

<P><A NAME="PartAndPartMortgage"></A><H3>Part and Part mortgage: </H3>part of the mortgage is 
calculated on a Capital and Interest basis, and the other part on an Interest 
only basis.
<P></P>

